## Common Mistakes

- Prompting the AI without including the specific section of the specification, leading to generic code that conflicts with existing architecture.
- Applying generated code without running tests, causing integration failures later in the cycle.
- Asking for complex business logic rules in a single prompt, resulting in oversimplified or incorrect AI-generated code.
- Ignoring generated code warnings (linting errors) and forcing the code into production.
- Not updating the SPEC.md after the AI helps implement a feature that changes the original scope.


## Best Practices

- Use the "Reference" feature: Always link or paste the relevant spec section into the chat window when asking Cursor AI to generate new logic.
- Implement in Vertical Slices: Do not generate all Models first and then all Routes. Instead, build a vertical slice (Model + Route + Controller) for one feature at a time to ensure the integration works.
- Maintain a "Spec-Impl" Checklist: Create a simple checklist in your README or Jira ticket. Mark items as 'Spec Defined' and 'Code Verified' to ensure you don't skip the validation step.
- Iterate on Error Messages: When debugging, do not just ask "This is broken." Instead, provide the error message, the file path, and a brief description of what the function is supposed to do based on the spec.
- Preserve Human Judgment: Use AI for speed on syntax and patterns, but verify the logic of loops, conditions, and data transformations manually.

